                    "company": "Single Resolution Board",
                    "description": "I first worked in Italian bank unit and then the Resolution Strategy, Processes and Methodology unit of the SRB.\n\nIn the Italian unit, I had responsibility for UniCredit. My tasks included coordinating preparation of the resolution plan, managing the SRM Internal Resolution Team and establishing UniCredit's resolution college. The college was the largest in the SRM, encompassing authorities from 14 Member States.\n\nIn my second role, I worked to develop and implement strategies and processes for the SRM. Notable tasks included:\n\n(i)\tBrexit:  developing the SRB\u2019s Brexit strategy, participating in the Brexit Contact Group established by the European Commission and briefing Board Members on potential impacts of a hard Brexit;\n\n(ii)\tMREL: development of the SRM\u2019s MREL policy, with a  focus on third country issuances, Brexit and retail investors. I also delivered internal training on policy implementation and represented the SRB at a press conference to explain the policy; and\n\n(iii)\tAsset separation tool (AST): developed the SRM\u2019s guidance note on the AST by convening an expert network, collating contributions from network members and drafting the final SRM guidance note.\n\nI also represented the SRB as follows:\n\n(iv)\tECB: led the renegotiation of the ECB/SRB MoU and participated in tripartite discussions with the European Commission on how to improve the SRMR;\n\n(v)\tEuropean Court of Auditors (ECA): I was tasked with explaining the policy choices taken by the SRB, educating the ECA as to the constraints under which the SRB operated in its start-up phase and negotiating the ECA's special report on the SRB (in both the consensual and adversarial phases); and\n\n(vi)\tIMF: I led the team representing the SRB during the IMF\u2019s Article IV Mission for the Euro Area, drafting responses to the IMF\u2019s questionnaire, marshalling internal resources and coordinating contacts between SRM NRAs and the IMF and coordinating with other Eurozone agencies.",
